            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Λεο<supplied reason="omitted">σ</supplied>θένης
                    <lb n="2"/>Λέπιδος
                    <lb n="3"/>καὶ Ἐράσμιος,
                    <lb n="4"/>ἔζησες ἔτ<supplied reason="omitted">η</supplied> κʹ,
                    <lb n="5"/><expan><abbr>μῆν</abbr><ex>ας</ex></expan>∙ δʹ ∙<expan><abbr>ἡμέρ</abbr><ex>ας</ex></expan> ηʹ.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <app loc="line4"><note><choice><reg>ἔζησας</reg><orig>ἔζησες</orig></choice></note></app>
                <p><!--external apparatus criticus (if applicable)--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Leosthenes, gentile e amabile, vivesti 20 anni, 4 mesi e 8 giorni</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Leosthenese, kind and lovable, you have lived for 20 years, 4 months and 8 days</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>After the name Λεοσθένης, the inscription presents the forms λέπιδος and ἐράσμιος, where λέπιδος could be a loanword from Latin lepidus 'pleasing', 'lovable'. Keibel and Wilamowitz took the two words as nicknames attributed to Leosthenes by his friends. Wilhelm (Wilhelm, Adolf. 1928 Wiener Studien, Zeitschrift für klassische Philologie. p. 227), followed by Drew Bear (Drew Bear 1972 p. 206), suggested instead that λέπιδος, just as the following ἐράσμιος, expresses the characteristics of the deceased person. If this were the case, I.Sicily 0857 would be an interesting case of bilingualism in Sicily, as Korhonen 2007 p. 294 suggested. It is noteworthy that Lepidus is not found in Sicily as a personal name, although there is one attestation of the PN Lepidia (I.Sicily 3242).</p>
                <p>The form ἔζησες has to be considered a solecism for ἔζησας. The inscription is an invocation to Leosthenes, the deceased.</p>
            </div>
